{
  "answer": "**In *Ślokāntara* (a medieval Kawi-language anthology of 84 Sanskrit verses—*śloka*—each followed by Old Javanese prose commentary), the term \"śloka\" appears literally once.**[^1]\n\nIt occurs in the commentary on verse 61 (*Ślo_61j*), where it refers metapoetically to the challenge of fully interpreting such verses:\n\n> A person who interprets the meaning of a *śloka* should not say that their understanding of the holy knowledge is complete. Even if the meaning of the scripture is multiplied a thousand times, one should still suspect that there is yet another meaning to the holy teachings.[^1]\n\nThe verses themselves are marked as *śloka* (e.g., *Ślo_01s*, *Ślo_02s*), but \"śloka\" is not used in their Sanskrit or the surrounding commentary except here.\n\n**The title *Ślokāntara* literally means \"verse-interval\" or \"between verses\" (*śloka* 'verse' + *antara* 'interval, difference, distinction').** In context, it evokes the explanatory *antara* (gaps/interludes) filled by the commentaries between the numbered verses—much like *bhāṣya* traditions. The text opens with \"Ślokāntara\" and closes \"Thus ends the Ślokāntara\".[^2][^3]\n\n[^1]: *Ślokāntara*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628-d7a628/01/translation/#p-02783f).\n[^2]: *Ślokāntara*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628-d7a628/01/translation/#p-aa8078).\n[^3]: *Ślokāntara*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-slokantara-d7a628-d7a628/01/translation/#p-404472).",
